{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17519879","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17519879"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T14:17:06+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T14:17:06+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"13099"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"13099","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/13099"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.02,0.02,0.81,0.04,0.13]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"5536"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"111344"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"5536","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/5536"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"13099"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"93472"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"11"},{"type":"tags","id":"27"},{"type":"tags","id":"65"},{"type":"tags","id":"1087"},{"type":"tags","id":"1936"},{"type":"tags","id":"2589"},{"type":"tags","id":"4174"},{"type":"tags","id":"4976"},{"type":"tags","id":"4982"},{"type":"tags","id":"4987"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"},{"type":"tags","id":"11635"},{"type":"tags","id":"11650"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"9450"},{"type":"contributions","id":"9742"},{"type":"contributions","id":"41695"},{"type":"contributions","id":"43384"},{"type":"contributions","id":"44735"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"111344","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/111344"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 76-year-old man presents to the General Practice clinic with a six-month history of gradually worsening shortness of breath on exertion and chronic non-productive cough. He initially noticed breathlessness when climbing two flights of stairs but attributed this to ageing. Over the past month, his symptoms have progressed such that he cannot walk 200 metres without becoming short of breath. He has a medical history of 45 pack-years of smoking, which he ceased at age 55. He takes no regular medications. He worked as an underground coal miner for 30 years before retiring. He reports wheezing during upper respiratory tract infections but denies chest pain.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, he appears well with vital signs within normal limits. Respiratory examination reveals equal bilateral breath sounds with no adventitious sounds.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EPulmonary function tests reveal FEV1 2.14L (60% predicted, expected \u226580%), FVC 70% (expected \u226580%), FEV1/FVC 86% (expected \u226570%), and DLCO 72% (expected \u226580%). Chest X-ray shows diffuse small, nodular, rounded opacities.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate next investigation?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["PET scan","Sputum cytology","High-resolution CT scan","Lung function tests with methacholine challenge","Bronchoscopy and transbronchial lung biopsy"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003ECoal workers\u0027 pneumoconiosis, also known as \u0027black lung disease\u0027, is a type of pneumoconiosis associated with prolonged coal dust exposure. Coal miners are at risk of both coal workers\u0027 pneumoconiosis and silicosis. Simple coal workers\u0027 pneumoconiosis is often asymptomatic, but patients with symptomatic disease typically present with progressive dyspnoea on exertion and non-productive cough. Complicated coal workers\u0027 pneumoconiosis with progressive massive fibrosis may present with severe dyspnoea, melanoptysis, pulmonary hypertension, and respiratory failure.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EHigh-resolution CT scan\u003C/strong\u003E is the most appropriate next investigation as it is more sensitive and specific than chest X-ray in detecting coalescing nodules, early progressive massive fibrosis, and cavitation. In coal workers\u0027 pneumoconiosis, imaging typically reveals diffuse, small, rounded opacities or nodules 1-5mm in size, predominantly in the upper lobes. The presence of at least one opacity \u003E10mm suggests progressive massive fibrosis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPET scan\u003C/strong\u003E would be indicated if there was clinical suspicion of malignancy, but given the occupational history and typical radiographic findings of pneumoconiosis, this is not the most appropriate next step.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESputum cytology\u003C/strong\u003E is used to detect malignant cells in sputum but has low sensitivity and would not be helpful in diagnosing pneumoconiosis. The clinical presentation and occupational history make pneumoconiosis more likely than lung cancer.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ELung function tests with methacholine challenge\u003C/strong\u003E are used to diagnose airway hyperresponsiveness in asthma. While this patient reports wheezing with respiratory infections, his pulmonary function tests show a restrictive pattern with reduced DLCO, which is inconsistent with asthma and more suggestive of interstitial lung disease.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EBronchoscopy and transbronchial lung biopsy\u003C/strong\u003E may be considered if the diagnosis remains uncertain after high-resolution CT, but it is invasive and not necessary as the first-line investigation given the classic occupational history and radiographic findings.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Coal workers\u0027 pneumoconiosis presents with progressive dyspnoea and chronic cough in patients with prolonged coal dust exposure.","High-resolution CT scan is more sensitive than chest X-ray for detecting early progressive massive fibrosis and cavitation in pneumoconiosis.","Pulmonary function tests in pneumoconiosis typically show a restrictive pattern with reduced DLCO."],"references":["Barber C, Fishwick D. Pneumoconiosis. Medicine. 2020 Jun 1;48(6):417-21. DOI: https://doi.org/10.1016/j.mpmed.2020.03.012","Nguyen JA, Salmi D. Educational Case: Pneumoconiosis. Academic Pathology. 2021 May 10;8:23742895211013530. DOI: https://doi.org/10.1177/23742895211013530"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"93472"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"13099"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"93472","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/93472"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-08-12T20:47:40+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-08-16T16:25:01+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"5536"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"111344"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"11","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/11"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udec1","name":"Respiratory Medicine","synonyms":["Pulmonology"],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"27","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/27"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc77","name":"Occupational/Environmental Medicine","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"65","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/65"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Investigations","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"update